{{Quote|In the center, the Tarasin had erected a kind of altar or monument. They said they did not worship there, but instead set up the monument as a celebration of life in the forest.|[[Reidi Artom]]|<ref name="CG">''[[Living Force Campaign Guide]]''</ref>}}
The '''Sacred ch'hala tree grove''' of the [[Tarasin]] laid deep in the [[Forest/Legends|forests]] of [[Cularin/Legends|Cularin]]. It included dozens of [[ch'hala tree]]s, some of them from around [[532 BBY/Legends|532 BBY]]. The trees caused hypnotic ripples of color, similar to the effect Tarasins get with their scales.<ref name="CG" />

There was a stone in the middle of the grove, commemorating the time when the Tarasin began living in sedentary tribes or ''irstats.'' The stone predated the grove.<ref name="CG" />

At least once in their lives, each Tarasin religious leader would make a pilgrimage to the sacred grove. They would return home with the cutting of a ch'hala tree, to plant near their irstat. The ''irstat-kes'' of any Tarasin irstat was supposed to meet there with her peers periodically.<ref name="CG" />

At the time of [[Reidi Artom]]'s exploration of Cularin in [[232 BBY/Legends|232 BBY]], there were about forty ch'hala trees in the grove, and by [[31 BBY/Legends|31 BBY]], there were almost thirty more. Although Artom was invited by the Tarasin, later shows of disrespect by outworlders shocked the Tarasins. The Tarasin forbid any alien to visit the Grove, except with a Tarasin escort, knowing that it would else attract thousands of curious people and scientists. No [[platform city]] was to be constructed nearer than 1,000 kilometers from the Grove.<ref name="CG" />

Though the grove was not stronger in [[The Force/Legends|the Force]] than any other source of life, sometimes [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] from the [[Almas Academy]] would go there to meditate. The isolation of the grove was calming and the flowing patterns on the ch'hala trees was almost hypnotic.<ref name="CG" />

